english:
  title: On Late Spring - A Note on Things Written and Shown to Official Yi
  author: Lim Yu-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    South and north of the pond, grass spreads like a cushion.
    Across the rippling clear waters, small fish dart and play.
    The bright moon has its appointed time, rising in the gathering dusk.
    Falling blossoms, mingled with tears, bid farewell to the waning spring.
    Neither cold nor hot—what a perfect season this is!
    Half-drunk, half-awake, the man of leisure knows no worry.
    There is a hidden scholar dwelling south of here,
    And in our chance meetings, we have become true friends.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem is composed of quoted lines, with attributions to various literary figures. Each couplet or phrase credits different poets and writers, creating a collaborative work that weaves together their voices.
  - key: ''
    value: The references include Tang poet Bai Juyi (樂天), Song literati Om Sukkyeong (舜欽), Ou Yangxiu (永叔), and other classical scholars, reflecting the author's engagement with both Chinese and Korean literary traditions.
  - key: ''
    value: The work addresses Official Li (李注簿), likely a government functionary, using seasonal imagery and philosophical leisure as themes for contemplation.
